{"author":{"id":"75732e82453cc4795a3b5d7bef7a9ce916b428e5bbe06161843f7392657be5c1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1440674878,"nonce":"IWFGYFh31ULiSADhuDd6SNp+aGs=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUxMDM0ODgxMTg=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/256","origin":"github"},"title":"Cython error: undefined symbol: PyUnicodeUCS4_DecodeUTF8","message":"I am wrapping a tool that makes use of Cython. I am using the package_cython_0_20_1 wrapper from IUC, and the package_python_2_7 wrapper from IUC. When I try to compile the tool, I crashes with the following error:\n\n_failed to import Cython: .../galaxy/tool-dependencies/cython/0.20.1/iuc/package_cython_0_20_1/749f11b9358a/lib/python/Cython-0.20.1-py2.7-linux-x86_64.egg/Cython/Compiler/Scanning.so: undefined symbol: PyUnicodeUCS4_DecodeUTF8_\n\nAfter some reading I found that this issue is most likely due to different compilation settings for Cython and Python ( http://forum.dato.com/discussion/84/importerror-undefined-symbol-pyunicodeucs4-decodeutf8 ). Unicode chars can be represented by 2 or by 4 bytes, where Cython expects the 4 bytes representation, and python is probably compiled with 2 bytes.\n\nFollowing the code at the bottom of this page:\nhttps://docs.python.org/2.7/faq/extending.html#when-importing-module-x-why-do-i-get-undefined-symbol-pyunicodeucs2\nThe python package from galaxy is indeed \"UCS2 build\", unlike most systems defaults.\n\nSo, package_python_2_7 and package_cython_0_20_1 break with each other because of this issue.\nDoes someone have a clue how to solve this; would the most appropriate solution be at the python or the cython side?\n\nThere are a few ways that might solve this:\n- Update the package_python_2_7 wrapper and compile with the following argument: _--enable-unicode=ucs4_\n  - This may lead to unexpected behavior in all packages that depend on package_python_2_7\n- Let the current cython package depend on package_python_2_7 during installation (if cython is installed with a ucs2-python binary, it automatically solves it during compilation)\n  - This may lead to unexpected behavior in all packages that depend on package_cython_0_20_1\n- Create a new package package_python_2_7_cython_0_20_1, that depends on python_2_7 and compiles cython_0_20_1\n  - This does not solve the actual problem, but is a handy workaround","files":null}]}